   120	This is a single-paragraph spec amendment, not a refactor. It
   121	preserves the v0 contract and tightens chapter 9's claim to match
   122	what the suite actually delivers.
   123	
   124	## 3. Scope
   125	
   126	### 3.1 In scope
   127	
   128	Two new chapter-9 §5 groups, with new scenario files under
   129	[`conformance/scenarios/`](../../conformance/scenarios/):
   130	
   131	#### 3.1.a Group `Integrator atomicity` — citing chapter 06 §3.4 + §5.3
   132	
   133	Asserts the wire-observable projection of the atomic-three invariant
   134	on the **two** wire-visible artifacts (field + event), and the
   135	no-overwrite half of repeat-promotion idempotency.
   136	
   137	- **cross-artifact-consistency-on-success.** Single test that asserts
   138	  both directions of the atomic-three (field, event) projection in
   139	  one composed assertion: after `POST /trials/{T}/integrate` returns
   140	  2xx, (1) GET `/trials/{T}` shows `trial_commit_sha == X`, AND
   141	  (2) the event log contains exactly one `trial.integrated` event
   142	  for T with `data.trial_commit_sha == X`, AND (3) the field's value
   143	  and the event's payload reference the **same** SHA — i.e. they
   144	  are derived from the same atomic write. The cross-SHA-equality
   145	  assertion is the chunk's central new content; the field-only and
   146	  event-only halves are already covered by the v1 `Integrate
   147	  idempotency` group. Cites: [chapter 06 §3.4](../../spec/v0/06-integrator.md)
   148	  atomic-write.
   149	- **divergent-resubmit-leaves-no-second-event.** The existing v1
   150	  `test_different_sha_returns_409` asserts the field is unchanged
   151	  but does **not** explicitly assert the event log shows exactly
   152	  one `trial.integrated` (not two). This test pins that AND that
   153	  the field's stored SHA is still the original — the §5.3
   154	  no-overwrite rule projected onto the event side. Cites: chapter 06
   155	  §5.3.
   156	
   157	The cross-consistency direction-dual test (event-implies-field as a
   158	distinct test) was considered and dropped: it is logically the same
   159	invariant as field-implies-event and adds little debug value over a
   160	single composed assertion. Likewise, "failed-integrate-leaves-no-
   161	artifacts" was considered but moved to the §3.1.b group, where it
   162	belongs (it is a §2 precondition rejection, not a §3.4 atomicity
   163	test).
   164	
   165	#### 3.1.b Group `Promotion preconditions` — citing chapter 06 §2
   166	
   167	Asserts the §2(a) status-precondition requirement across the two
   168	**non-`starting`** terminal-error trial statuses (`error`,
   169	`eval_error`). The §2(b) commit_sha-set precondition is not
   170	independently wire-observable in v0 (per §2 above); a wire-only suite
   171	covers it only transitively through (a). The §2(c) branch-reachability
   172	precondition is off-wire in v0 (per §2 above); a future binding
   173	chapter MAY add it. The existing v1
   174	`test_integrate_against_non_success_trial_returns_409` covers (a) for
   175	the `starting` status; the two new tests below cover (a) for the
   176	remaining two non-`starting` non-`success` statuses, completing the
   177	status vocabulary.
   178	
   179	Each test asserts the **end-state**, not just the wire response, per
   180	the chunk-11c "end-state, not endpoint" pattern (
   181	[`conformance/README.md`](../../conformance/README.md)): the response
   182	is 4xx in `eden://error/invalid-precondition`, AND the trial's
   183	`trial_commit_sha` is unset, AND no `trial.integrated` event was
   184	appended for T. The composite end-state pins the §3.4 rollback-half
   185	"a failed write produces neither field nor event" without needing a
   186	separate §3.4 test for it.
   187	
   188	- **`error` trial → 409 invalid-precondition + no artifacts.** §2 says
   189	  "trials in `error` ... MUST NOT receive a `trial/*` commit." Cites
   190	  chapter 06 §2.
   191	- **`eval_error` trial → 409 invalid-precondition + no artifacts.**
   192	  Same MUST, different status. Cites §2.
   193	
   194	That's **4 new scenarios across two new groups**, plus the spec
   195	amendment to chapter 9 §4 + §5 index.
   196	
   197	### 3.2 Out of scope (deferred)
   198	
   199	Per §2 above, all of the following remain explicitly NOT asserted by
   200	the v1+roles+integrator suite. The amended chapter 9 §4 records this
   201	as deliberate, not an oversight:
   202	
   203	- §1.3 work/* discipline.
   204	- §1.4 reachability check.
   205	- §3.2 squash shape.
   206	- §3.3 commit message format.
   207	- §4.x eval-manifest path/shape/contents.
   208	- §5.1 partial-write rollback (server-side internal; wire only sees
   209	  the post-rollback state, which the §3.1.b precondition tests
   210	  pin via their composite end-state assertion).
   211	- §5.2 ref-durability.
   212	
   213	A future spec lineage that introduces a "git-access conformance
   214	contract" (the IUT exposes its bare-repo path through an extended
   215	adapter) MAY add a new level (e.g., `v2+integrator-git`) that asserts
   216	these. That is **not** chunk 11d.
   217	
   218	### 3.3 Non-goals
   219	
   220	- No changes to the harness adapter contract (`IutAdapter` /
   221	  `IutHandle`). Git access is not a v1+roles+integrator IUT contract;
   222	  see §3.2.
   223	- No changes to `eden_storage` or `eden_wire`. The reference impl
   224	  already passes the chapter-06 §3.4 wire projection (chunk-11b's
   225	  `Integrate idempotency` group covers most of it; the new group's
   226	  delta is cross-artifact consistency, which the reference impl's
   227	  composite-commit primitive already enforces).
   228	- No changes to the integrator package (`eden_git`). The integrator's
   229	  squash/manifest behavior is not under conformance assertion in v0.
   230	
   231	## 4. The "end-state, not endpoint" pattern (carried forward from 11c)
   232	
   233	For the §2 precondition tests, the rejection point in the IUT's pipeline
   234	is implementation-defined (the reference impl rejects synchronously at
   235	the wire layer with 409 invalid-precondition; a different IUT might
   236	defer the check to an async integrator background task). Per the
   237	chunk-11c codified pattern in
   238	[`conformance/README.md`](../../conformance/README.md) "Asserting
   239	end-state, not endpoint", these tests pin the **end-state**: trial is
   240	not promoted, no `trial.integrated` event, `trial_commit_sha` unset —

