./AGENTS.md:70:| `uv run python conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py` | Verify every conformance test's docstring cites a real spec section. |
./AGENTS.md:172:+ **Conformance assertions need three-legged traceability: group identity + MUST citation + group-relevance.** When adding a scenario to [`conformance/scenarios/`](conformance/scenarios/), three checks are gated by [`conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py`](conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py) (run in CI after pytest): (1) the file declares a module-level `CONFORMANCE_GROUP = "<group name>"` matching one of the chapter-9 §5 index groups; (2) the test docstring's first line cites `spec/v0/<chapter>.md §<sec>` whose section text (or any ancestor section) contains a `\bMUST\b` token; (3) the citation lies inside the declared group's chapter-9 §5 entry (or a descendant section). The three legs together prevent group bleed (groups that share a cited section, e.g. several §7 producers) AND identity-only misclassification (a file declaring any group regardless of what its tests cite). Phase-11 round-2/3/4 codex-review iterations all turned on these legs missing — both single-leg and dual-leg variants permitted regressions. If the assertion describes behavior the reference impl exhibits but no spec MUST mandates, the choice is to amend the spec (so the assertion is grounded) or drop the assertion; codifying impl observations as conformance assertions silently creates a second source of truth and locks third-party implementations into reference-impl quirks.
