./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11-chunk-11a-11b-conformance-harness/impl/20260501T122226/0-review.md:7:- Bug — [check_citations.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py:23): the plan’s load-bearing rule was “every scenario assertion must cite a normative MUST,” and the tooling was supposed to reject SHOULD/MAY citations and verify chapter-9 §5 coverage. The implementation only checks that a cited section exists and that certain filenames exist later in the file. It never inspects whether the citation points at normative MUST language, and it does not derive coverage from chapter 9 at all. That leaves the core conformance-discipline rule unenforced. Fix by parsing chapter 9’s scenario index, resolving each cited section’s text, and rejecting non-MUST citations.
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11c-role-contracts/20260501T175638/1.patch:145: - `conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py` — untouched.
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11c-role-contracts/20260501T175638/1.patch:147: 1. `uv run python conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py`
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11-chunk-11a-11b-conformance-harness/impl/20260501T122226/1-review.md:3:2. Risk — [check_citations.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py:35) and [check_citations.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py:126): the MUST-check is fixed, but the chapter-9 coverage guard is still weaker than the plan. It hardcodes group names/file names instead of reading `spec/v0/09-conformance.md §5`, and it treats “file has tests” as coverage rather than “group has at least one valid citing test.” That means chapter-9 drift is still not actually detected the way plan §I described. Fix by parsing the §5 index from chapter 9 and counting valid citations per group, not raw file presence.
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11-chunk-11a-11b-conformance-harness/impl/20260501T122226/1-review.md:7:The revised code is materially better. The suite and citation tool both run clean here: `uv run pytest -q conformance/` passed with 86 tests in 48.83s, and `uv run python conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py` passed with 85 scenario citations. I would not call it fully clear for commit/PR yet because of the remaining partial-startup leak and the still-weaker-than-planned chapter-9 coverage guard.
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11-chunk-11a-11b-conformance-harness/impl/20260501T122226/0.md:33:| `conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py` | Walks scenario docstrings; verifies every cite resolves AND every chapter-9 §5 group has ≥ 1 citing test | §I |
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11-chunk-11a-11b-conformance-harness/impl/20260501T122226/0.md:57:| `.github/workflows/ci.yml` | New `conformance` job: uv sync + pytest conformance/ + directionality grep + check_citations.py | §H |
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11-chunk-11a-11b-conformance-harness/impl/20260501T122226/2-review.md:1:- Risk — [check_citations.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py:150) and [check_citations.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py:228): the new chapter-9 coverage guard parses the §5 table correctly, but it still treats “same spec citation” as “same scenario group.” That is too permissive for groups that intentionally share citations. I verified this by simulating the suite without `test_error_vocabulary.py`: the tool still considers the `Error vocabulary closure` group covered, because `test_problem_json.py` and `test_status_codes.py` also cite `07-wire-protocol.md §7`. The same structural problem applies anywhere two groups share a cited section. The fix is to add explicit group identity on the test side, such as a module-level `CONFORMANCE_GROUP = "Error vocabulary closure"` or a dedicated marker/fixture per group, and then check chapter-9 coverage against that explicit group mapping rather than citation overlap alone.
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11-chunk-11a-11b-conformance-harness/impl/20260501T122226/2-review.md:3:Everything else I checked looks good. I reran `uv run python conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py` and `uv run pytest -q conformance/`; both passed, with the suite green at `86 passed in 49.13s`. I would not clear this for commit/PR yet because the chapter-9 drift guard is still not enforcing group coverage the way the plan says it should.
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11-chunk-11a-11b-conformance-harness/impl/20260501T122226/4-review.md:5:`uv run python conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py` passed, and `uv run pytest -q conformance/` passed with `86 passed in 49.87s`.
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11-chunk-11a-11b-conformance-harness/impl/20260501T122226/3-review.md:1:- Risk — [check_citations.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py:233) and [check_citations.py](/Users/ericalt/Documents/eden/conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py:250): the new `CONFORMANCE_GROUP` identity fix solves the cross-group overlap problem, but the tool now dropped the other half of the guard. `group_to_valid_tests` is populated by “any valid citation in this file,” and the final coverage check only asks whether the group has any such test. It no longer verifies that the test’s citation matches one of that group’s chapter-9 §5 citations. In other words, a file declaring `CONFORMANCE_GROUP = 'Error vocabulary closure'` would still count as coverage even if every test in that file cited an unrelated MUST. The fix is to combine both checks: require explicit `CONFORMANCE_GROUP` identity and require each counted test’s citation to match that group’s parsed chapter-9 citation set.
./docs/plans/review/eden-phase-11-chunk-11a-11b-conformance-harness/impl/20260501T122226/3-review.md:3:Everything else I checked looks good, and the verification is still clean here: `uv run python conformance/src/conformance/tools/check_citations.py` passed and `uv run pytest -q conformance/` passed with `86 passed in 49.13s`. I’m not ready to clear it for commit/PR until that last citation-to-group relevance check is restored.
